{
  "query": "How does rotational burning compare to leaving unburned patches during prescribed fires for butterfly populations in US prairies?",
  "relevant_summary": "Evidence from US prairies and similar open habitats shows that leaving unburned patches during prescribed fires was associated with increases in Karner blue butterfly abundance over 2\u20133 years, greater abundance for six of nine specialist species (with one lower and two similar), and confirmed use of all surveyed unburned patches by Karner blues [3879]. In contrast, rotational burning produced mixed outcomes: butterfly richness and/or abundance were sometimes higher than on unmanaged or annually burned sites, but often varied with time since last burn (generally higher more than 1\u20134 years after burning), and some taxa or regions showed lower abundance under rotational burning than under other management or unmanaged conditions; specific results included similar Karner blue abundance to unmanaged sites, variable responses among fritillaries (including lower abundance for some species in some regions), and patterns where regal fritillary abundance was higher in prairies managed on a three-year rotation or four years post-burn than in more recently or much longer unburned sites [3883].",
  "action_ids": [
    "3879",
    "3883"
  ]
}

