{
  "query": "What does the evidence say about the long-term success of re-establishing butterfly populations through translocation or captive-release?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across 16 studies of translocations within former range, many translocated butterfly and moth populations persisted 2\u201312 years and increased in abundance, though some persisted 1\u201349 years and colonized new sites while others died out within 0\u20137 years; one review found 25% of translocated/released captive-bred populations survived \u22653 years, 38% died out within three years, and only 8% were known to survive >10 years; another review reported large copper populations survived up to 38 years but ultimately died out or required further releases; in specific cases, survival of translocated large copper caterpillars exceeded that of released captive-bred caterpillars, large blue caterpillar survival was higher when placed in ant nests without queens, and 19 years after translocation large blue genetic diversity matched the source population [3909]. Across 13 studies of captive-bred releases, several populations released as eggs, caterpillars, pupae or adults persisted 2\u201328 years and increased, sometimes with continued rearing or supplementation, but other releases died out after 1, 2 or 12 years or required further releases; a replicated study found 3/10 barberry carpet moth releases established with at least one persisting five years; a review across the UK and Ireland reported 25% of captive-bred/translocated populations survived >3 years, 38% died within that time, and only 8% were known to survive >10 years; released captive-bred large copper caterpillars had lower survival than captive, wild or translocated caterpillars [3914].",
  "action_ids": [
    "3909",
    "3914"
  ]
}

