  "query": "How do different methods of harvesting timber, such as selective logging and shelterwood harvesting, compare to clearcutting in their impact on moth diversity in US forests?",
  "relevant_summary": "In US forests, shelterwood harvesting was associated with higher macro\u2011moth species richness than clearcutting or patch\u2011cutting, with richness similar to thinned and unharvested stands in one controlled, before\u2011after study; two replicated, controlled, before\u2011after studies found moth richness under shelterwood was similar to single\u2011tree and group\u2011selection harvesting or clearcutting but recovered faster after shelterwood than after group selection or clearcutting, while remaining lower than in unharvested forest (3871). For selective (single\u2011tree) logging, a replicated, controlled, before\u2011after US study found moth species richness was similar to group selection and clearcutting, but lower than in unharvested forest (3867). For group selection and thinning, one controlled, before\u2011after US study found thinning produced higher macro\u2011moth richness than patch\u2011cutting or clearcutting and similar richness to unharvested forest; two replicated, controlled, before\u2011after studies found group selection had moth richness similar to single\u2011tree selection and clearcutting, with richness recovering at a similar rate to clearcutting and slower than shelterwood (3868, 3871).",
  "action_ids": [
    "3871",
