{
  "query": "What are the documented effects of excluding different types of herbivores on butterfly and moth populations?",
  "relevant_summary": "- A replicated, site comparison study in the UK found higher density of pearl-bordered fritillary at sites fenced to exclude grazing animals than at unfenced sites [3885].\n- Across ten studies on excluding vertebrate herbivores: two of four replicated studies reported greater species richness of butterflies and macro-moths in forest plots fenced to exclude or reduce non-native pigs and deer, while two studies of elk exclusion showed mixed effects on richness depending on fire intensity and year; grassland plots fenced to exclude elk had similar butterfly richness to unfenced plots; a global systematic review found no effect of reducing/removing grazing or browsing on butterfly and moth species richness in temperate and boreal forests [3891].\n- For abundance, five of eight studies reported higher abundance of butterflies, moths, caterpillars, rare macro\u2011moths, or New Forest burnet moths in plots fenced to exclude or reduce deer, sheep, pigs, or large herbivores (one of these also found similar total macro\u2011moth abundance between treatments); two elk-exclosure studies reported mixed effects by fire intensity and year, with grassland elk exclosures showing similar butterfly abundance; a forest fenced to exclude sika deer had similar overall moth abundance but lower tree\u2011feeding moth abundance; a global systematic review reported increased abundance of butterflies and moths when grazing/browsing was reduced or removed [3891].\n- In a paired, controlled study in the Netherlands, Glanville fritillary caterpillar nests had higher survival (100% vs 88%) and less damage in grassland fenced to exclude sheep than in a grazed area [3891].",
