{
  "query": "In agricultural landscapes, how does restoring grassland from arable land compare to restoring grassland from abandoned meadows for butterfly communities?",
  "relevant_summary": "Restoring arable land to permanent grassland: Butterfly communities on grasslands seeded from bare soil became increasingly similar to existing high-quality grasslands over the first 10 years after establishment, and older sown grasslands using competitive mixes had a greater proportion of specialist butterflies than newer grasslands sown with less competitive species that required periodic re-seeding (3929). Species richness of butterflies and moths was higher on 4\u20135-year-old created grasslands and abandoned cropland than on conventionally managed grassland or cultivated farms, and richness and abundance were higher when seed mixes included forbs compared to grass-only mixes; abundance on restored grassland was similar to semi-natural grasslands and higher than in crop fields, though abundance did not increase with time since restoration; after adopting a scheme including arable reversion, abundance of several butterfly species and large moths increased on a farm (3929). Restoring semi-natural grassland from abandoned meadows (via scrub clearance and reintroduction of grazing or mowing): Restored sites had butterfly communities different from existing species-rich grasslands and did not become more similar over time (3955). Species richness was similar to, or lower than, unrestored or continuously managed grassland depending on study (3955). Abundance was often lower than on unmanaged, abandoned grasslands for many species, though some species had higher abundance on restored grasslands than on continuously grazed sites; in other cases, abundance on restored sites was similar to unmanaged or continuously managed grasslands; in one case, egg density of blue-spot hairstreak was higher on scrub-cut restored grasslands than on unrestored or continuously managed grasslands (3955).",
