{
  "query": "What are the observed effects of ceasing grassland management, either by stopping mowing or grazing, on butterfly abundance and diversity?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across multiple studies, ceasing mowing or grazing produced mixed outcomes for butterflies and moths. Community composition sometimes remained similar to managed sites, but after abandonment the community became dominated by generalist species with fewer generations per year (3957, 3956). For diversity, after stopping mowing, five of seven studies reported similar species richness to managed grasslands, with some cases of lower richness after 6\u201313 years or >50 years, and one case of higher richness when meadows were left uncut all summer (3957). After stopping grazing, six of nine studies reported similar richness to grazed sites, one found greater richness than sheep-grazed grassland, two found lower richness after >5\u201320 years or many years, one found higher richness where grazing ceased 2\u20139 years ago than in >10-year abandonments or currently grazed, and three studies reported higher richness in grasslands abandoned 4, 5\u201310 or >10 years compared to extensively or commercially grazed, with similarity to lightly grazed in two cases (3956). For abundance, stopping mowing led to lower abundance in some studies, higher abundance in others, species-specific or habitat-shifted responses (woodland/hedgerow species increasing, grassland/farmland species decreasing), local extinctions in some cases (e.g., silver-studded blue), mixed species responses across regions, and time-since-abandonment effects (e.g., similar abundance after ~6 years but lower after >25 years with no caterpillars) (3957). After stopping grazing, six of 20 studies found higher abundance than grazed (sometimes only vs intensive grazing), four found lower, four found similar, four reported species-specific mixed responses, one found density higher 2\u20139 years post-cessation than in >10-year abandonments or currently grazed, local extinctions occurred for large blue and silver-studded blue in some meadows, species-specific responses included clouded Apollo being lower than lightly grazed but higher than heavily grazed, and one European review reported benefits for six of 67 species of conservation concern (3956).",
  "action_ids": [
    "3957",
    "3956"
  ]
}

