  "query": "What is the state of the evidence regarding the success of restoring habitats after mining and quarrying activities for butterfly and moth conservation?",
  "relevant_summary": "Four studies (two in the Czech Republic, one in the UK, one in New Zealand) assessed restoring or creating habitats after mining/quarrying for butterflies and moths, with mixed outcomes (3862). Community composition: a replicated, paired, site comparison in the Czech Republic found 15% of 380 invertebrate species (including 208 moth species) occurred only on flattened spoil heaps, while 30% occurred only on unflattened heaps (3862). Richness/diversity: replicated, paired, site comparisons in the Czech Republic found technically restored quarries had lower species richness of butterflies and day\u2011flying moths than quarries left to restore naturally, and flattened spoil heaps had lower moth species richness than unflattened spoil heaps (3862). Population response: a replicated, randomized, controlled UK study on slate waste tips found fertilizer application on trees did not change caterpillar abundance compared to unfertilized trees, and a New Zealand site comparison found a peat bog restored after mining supported similar density and caterpillar size of the Fred the thread moth to undisturbed bogs (3862). No behaviour studies were reported (3862).",
  "action_ids": [
