  "query": "How does managing semi-natural open habitats with rough grazing compare to using prescribed fire for butterfly and moth populations?",
  "relevant_summary": "Rough grazing in semi-natural habitats: Across nine studies, species richness was often similar to unmanaged or cut areas in calcareous dunes and shrubsteppe, while light sheep grazing on saltmarsh increased micro-moth species richness compared to moderate/heavy grazing and was similar to ungrazed marsh; upland rough grassland under livestock grazing had higher butterfly richness than improved grassland (3944). Abundance responses were mixed: higher abundance for large copper eggs and some butterfly species under cattle/pony grazing in fens and dunes, similar abundance to ungrazed in shrubsteppe, lower abundance in meadow steppe under livestock, and on saltmarsh light grazing increased total micro-moth abundance and some caterpillars compared to moderate/heavy grazing or ungrazed, though other caterpillars were lower under grazing than ungrazed; upland rough grassland had higher butterfly abundance than improved grassland (3944). Occupancy/use: brown argus and Alcon large blue were more likely to occupy grazed calcareous dunes and heathland than unmanaged or differently managed sites (3944). Prescribed fire in open habitats: Species richness of butterflies was often similar between burned and unburned shrubland plots and field margins; patch-burning in pastures yielded lower richness than rotational grazing, similar to some grazed/mown pastures, and higher than continuous grazing (3882). Abundance responses were mixed: increased abundance for heath fritillary adults, marsh fritillary caterpillar webs, and Fender\u2019s blue caterpillars/eggs one or more years after burning compared to before or to unburned/grazed land, but decreased abundance for Brenton blue eggs/adults, rosy marsh moth caterpillars, and regal fritillary on burned sites versus unburned; some species (e.g., regal fritillary, arogos skipper) were less abundant on burned prairies than hayed/grazed, while generalists and some species (e.g., purplish copper) were more abundant on burned than hayed/grazed; one review reported occasional grassland burning benefitted 10/67 species of conservation concern (3882). Survival/occupancy: Fender\u2019s blue caterpillar survival was lower one year post-burn than in unburned plots, while marsh fritillary occupancy of fen meadows was similar among burned, grazed, and unmanaged sites (3882). Overall, both approaches showed mixed, species- and context-dependent effects on richness, abundance, survival, and occupancy across studies (3944, 3882).",
