{
  "query": "What are the benefits of planting new hedges and managing existing ones for butterfly and moth conservation on farmland?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across multiple studies, established hedgerows were associated with higher species richness of butterflies and macro\u2011moths than in\u2011field beetle banks, crops or pasture, though richness was sometimes similar to grass banks between fields [3976]. Hedgerows also supported higher abundances of butterflies, moths/macro\u2011moths and gatekeepers than beetle banks, grass margins without hedgerows, field interiors, or locations 5\u201310 m from hedgerows, while one study found similar abundance to grass banks between fields [3976]. Moths recorded close to hedgerows were more likely to fly parallel to them than moths further away [3976]. Within planted hedgerows, gorse, oak and blackthorn hosted more species of arthropods, including caterpillars, than commonly planted hawthorn [3976]. Managing existing hedgerows to increase structural complexity or include trees was linked to higher species richness or diversity of butterflies and macro\u2011moths than simpler hedgerows without trees [3975]. Cutting regimes that allow incremental growth, cutting once every 2\u20133 years, or autumn cutting were associated with higher abundance of adult butterflies and moths, moth caterpillars and pupae, and more brown hairstreak eggs than annual, same\u2011size cutting, although in some cases caterpillar/pupa abundance was similar between regimes [3975]. Hedgerows kept 1\u20132 m tall had higher butterfly species richness than those kept below 1 m, while one study reported more adult butterflies in hedgerows maintained below 1 m; fields with larger\u2011volume hedgerows showed higher butterfly richness and abundance in one of two years [3975]. Hedgerows with trees or more complex structure had higher abundance of butterflies and pale shining brown moths, though some studies found similar total macro\u2011moth abundance with or without trees [3975]. Scalloped hedgerow edges supported more brown hairstreak eggs than straight edges, and field margins next to hedgerow trees had higher abundance of most shrub\u2011/tree\u2011feeding moth species than margins away from trees [3975]. Laid or coppiced hedgerows had higher butterfly abundance than unmanaged hedgerows, but one study found managed hedgerows had lower caterpillar abundance than remnant hedgerows [3975].",
