{
  "query": "What are the typical timeframes for butterfly and moth population responses following forest management interventions like clearing, coppicing, and thinning?",
  "relevant_summary": "Clearing/opening patches: In one study, butterfly abundance and species richness declined over the first three years after clearing, though cleared patches supported higher butterfly abundance than unmanaged or coppiced areas in some cases (3938). In the UK, heath fritillary abundance was greater 2\u20134 years after clearance than in the first year or 7\u201311 years after clearance (3938). Thinning: Across multiple studies, one, two or four years after thinning (often combined with burning, mulching or nearby felling), butterfly abundance and species richness were higher than before management or in unmanaged woodland (3940). Coppicing: Butterfly species richness was greater two years after coppicing than in areas coppiced >15 years ago (3939). Butterfly abundance was higher in woodland coppiced two, two\u2013four, five\u2013seven or 12\u201315 years ago than in woodland coppiced 5\u201311 or >15 years ago (3939). For moths, abundance was similar in woodland coppiced 1\u20134, 5\u20138 and 12\u201320 years ago, and macro-moth abundance was lower in coppiced woodland than in mature forest with no change across coppice ages (3939).",
