{
  "query": "In European forests, how do the effects of coppicing and clearing patches compare for butterfly and moth communities?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across European forests, both coppicing and clearing patches tend to increase butterfly metrics but often reduce macro\u2011moth metrics compared to mature or unmanaged woodland. Coppiced sites frequently had higher butterfly species richness and abundance (including heath fritillary), with different-aged coppice supporting different moth and butterfly communities, while macro\u2011moths were less species\u2011rich and less abundant than in mature forest [3939]. Cleared or opened patches generally had higher butterfly species richness and abundance than unmanaged or closed\u2011canopy forest, especially in larger clearings, but showed lower macro\u2011moth species richness (and, on wider rides, lower macro\u2011moth abundance) than mature forest; butterfly richness and abundance could decline in the first three years after clearing [3938].",
