{
  "query": "What is the evidence for the success of re-establishing butterfly populations through translocation and captive-breeding programs?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across 16 studies of translocations within former range, many translocated butterfly and moth populations persisted 2\u201312 years and increased in abundance, though others died out within 0\u20137 years; a review found 25% of translocated/released captive-bred butterfly populations survived \u22653 years, 38% died out within 3 years, and only 8% were known to survive >10 years; in some cases, translocated populations persisted up to decades but ultimately died out or needed supplementation; survival of translocated large copper caterpillars exceeded that of released captive-bred caterpillars; and a reintroduced large blue population retained genetic diversity similar to its source after 19 years (all from 3909). For releases of captive-bred individuals (13 studies), several populations persisted 2\u201328 years and increased (sometimes with continued rearing or supplementary releases), but others died out within 1\u201312 years or required further releases; in one replicated study, 3/10 released barberry carpet moth populations established, and at least one persisted 5 years; a review across the UK and Ireland reported 25% of captive-bred/translocated populations survived >3 years, 38% died out within that time, and only 8% were known to survive >10 years; and multiple studies found released captive-bred large copper caterpillars had lower survival than captive, wild, or translocated caterpillars (all from 3914). Translocations outside known range (4 studies) showed mixed outcomes: two studies reported populations (including one involving captive-bred individuals) that persisted and increased over 8 and 28 years, while another died out within one year; a long-established introduced population maintained genetic diversity comparable to its source (all from 3911).",
