{
  "query": "What are the most effective ways to manage field margins in arable landscapes for increasing butterfly abundance?",
  "relevant_summary": "- Planting wildflower/nectar flower strips in field margins was associated with higher abundance of all butterflies, generalist and specialist butterflies, and meadow brown compared to conventional or unsown margins, cropped fields/margins, and conventional grassland; margins sown with wildflowers also had higher butterfly abundance than grass-only field margins; farms with wildflower strips had higher abundance of butterflies and micro-moths than conventionally managed farms; plots sown with lucerne had higher butterfly abundance than plots sown with borage, chicory or sainfoin [3932].\n- In uncultivated margins, butterfly abundance was often lower than in sown margins, but margins that were not cut, or only cut in spring/autumn, had higher butterfly abundance than margins cut in summer; wider margins had higher butterfly abundance than conventional-width margins; margins located closer to existing grassland had higher butterfly and burnet moth abundance; uncultivated margins had higher abundance of butterflies and day-flying moths than cereal fields or cropped field edges [3981].\n- Leaving uncropped, cultivated margins/plots: fields with wider margins between crops had higher butterfly abundance in one of two years; farms under agri-environment schemes (including uncropped cultivated margins) had higher abundance of butterflies and micro-moths than conventionally managed farms; farms with enhanced agri-environment options (including uncropped, cultivated margins) had higher abundance of some butterflies but lower abundance of others than simpler schemes [3923].",
